functional: Adds tools to call a procedure on arguments packed as a std::tuple, etc.

This is useful if you need to temporarily store the arguments (e.g. in a std::tuple)
and later call the procedure.

Besides std::tuple, arguments can be stored as std::pair, std::array, or any
type modeling the `Tuple` concept (see concept.hpp).

Example: using `std::tuple` as a container for arguments
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
int f(int i, char c, float f) {
  ...
}

// ...
auto args = std::make_tuple(5, 'a', 3.14f);
int res = apply(f, args);
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

It is also possible to transform a procedure expecting n arguments to another one
expecting one `Tuple` of arguments. This is a form a currying.

Example: Transforming a procedure to a `Tuple` arguments one.
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
int f(int i, int j) {
  ...
};

// ...
auto args = std::make_pair(34, 45);
auto f2 = apply(f); // f2 expects a `Tuple` that unpacks to 2 arguments.
auto res1 = f2(args); // equivalent to `apply(f, args)`
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

